  1. Perform a one-way ANOVA to test the differences in \(Petal.Length\) by \(Species\). Use the 5% significance level. Also, perform a multiple comparison test to determine the order of petal lengths by species. Write the relevant details on your exam paper.
    Solution
    Model: \(y_{ij} = \mu + \tau_i + \varepsilon_{ij}\) where
  • \(y_{ij}\) is petal length for \(i^{th}\) population (setosa, versicolor, virginica) and \(j^{th}\) observation within that population.
  • \(\mu\) is grand mean for all populations.
  • \(\tau_i\) is the population effect of \(i^{th}\) population.
  • \(\varepsilon_{ij}\) is the error term (random variation), which is independent and normally distributed with \(\mu_{\epsilon} = 0\) and standard deviation \(\sigma_{\epsilon}\).

\(H_0: \tau_{setosa} = \tau_{versicolor} = \tau_{virginica} = 0\)
\(H_a:\) at least one populations effect is non-zero.
T.S.: \(F = \frac{MSTrt}{MSE}\)

iris.aov <- aov(formula=Petal.Length ~ Species, data=iris)
summary(iris.aov)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Species       2  437.1  218.55    1180 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   147   27.2    0.19                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

p-value is less than 5%. We reject the null hypothesis. At least one populations petal length is different from the rest of the populations.

After it is known that at least one of the populations was different, pairwise comparisons can be used to determine which populations are different.

Tukey pairwise test

TukeyHSD(x=iris.aov, conf.level=0.95)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = Petal.Length ~ Species, data = iris)
## 
## $Species
##                       diff     lwr     upr p adj
## versicolor-setosa    2.798 2.59422 3.00178     0
## virginica-setosa     4.090 3.88622 4.29378     0
## virginica-versicolor 1.292 1.08822 1.49578     0

The output shows each pairwise comparison: the mean difference (diff) and the confidence interval (lwr and upr) of their difference. p adj is the p-value. With p-values of zero, the differences for each group is significant.

An equivalent Tukey pairwise test can done using the agricolae library. The HSD.test() function requires following parameters:

  • y: ANOVA object that comes from using the aov() function.
  • trt: The exact name of treatment variable that was entered in aov() function.
    • not sure how to enter multiple treatments for two-way ANOVA.

The default for signficance is \(\alpha=0.05\).

library(agricolae)
## Warning: package 'agricolae' was built under R version 3.1.3
tukey.pairs <- HSD.test(y=iris.aov, trt="Species")
tukey.pairs$groups
##          trt means M
## 1 virginica  5.552 a
## 2 versicolor 4.260 b
## 3 setosa     1.462 c

The column M are groupings. If two or more treatments are not considered different from each other, they would be assigned the same letter. Here we see that each treatment has a different letter, so they are all different from each other.

Fishers Least Significant Difference
There doesnt appear to be a Fisher LSD test in base R. Use LSD.test() function from the agricolae package. See above for parameter descriptions.

library(agricolae)
fisher.pairs <- LSD.test(y=iris.aov, trt="Species")
fisher.pairs$groups
##          trt means M
## 1 virginica  5.552 a
## 2 versicolor 4.260 b
## 3 setosa     1.462 c

Interpretation is the same as output of HSD.test().
